(ordinary-world-relationships
  :count 8

  (piece
    :id \"rr-01-neighbors-who-dont-know-each-other\"
    :title \"Neighbors who don't know each other\"
    :prose
    \"The couple in 3B and the couple in 3C have lived on the same floor
for six years. They nod at each other in the hallway. They know each
other's names because there's a maintenance sheet on the bulletin
board downstairs. But they don't know each other.

3B is a schoolteacher and a nurse. 3C is a graphic designer and a
paralegal. They would probably like each other. They've never had a
reason to find out.

Once a package for 3C got left at 3B's door. 3B knocked on 3C's door
and handed it over. 'Wrong door,' 3B said. 'Thanks,' 3C said. Both
smiled. That was the longest conversation they've ever had.

The building has an annual holiday party in December. Half the
tenants show up. Neither 3B nor 3C usually does. Once, five years
ago, they were both there for twenty minutes. They didn't talk to
each other. They talked to other people.

This is a specific kind of relationship. Not friendship, not
strangers. Something in between. The building has dozens of them.
Most buildings do.

Neither couple thinks about it much. But when 3B moved out — three
years later, to a house upstate — 3C actually felt something small.
Not sadness. A shape leaving.\")

  (piece
    :id \"rr-02-a-first-date\"
    :title \"A first date\"
    :prose
    \"They agreed to meet at a bar in Fort Greene. Neither had been there
before. Both looked it up beforehand — she looked at the menu, he
looked at the reviews.

She got there five minutes early on purpose. She wanted the seat
facing the door. He got there three minutes early because he was
nervous. He didn't know she was already inside.

They both saw each other at the same time. Small awkward wave. She
stood. He walked over. He hugged her lightly. She hugged back but
kept it short.

They both ordered a drink. Neither wanted a second drink yet but they
both said 'yeah' when the bartender asked.

The conversation was okay. Not amazing. Not bad. They found out they
both grew up in Ohio, in different towns, which was more common than
they expected. He talked about his sister. She talked about her mother.

An hour in he asked if she wanted to walk. She said yes. They walked
along Lafayette. It was cool for June. The trees were full.

At the end of the walk he asked if he could see her again. She said
yes.

Neither of them said 'I had a great time.' They said 'this was nice.'

She got in a cab. He walked home. He was tired but not disappointed.
She was slightly excited but not thrilled.

Six months later they would be dating. A year later they would live
together. Five years later they would decide not to get married. Ten
years later he would remember the walk on Lafayette and the way she
said 'this was nice.'\")

  (piece
    :id \"rr-03-a-shared-bathroom\"
    :title \"A shared bathroom\"
    :prose
    \"Two roommates, one bathroom. He gets up at seven. She gets up at
seven-fifteen. They have worked out a schedule. He is out of the
bathroom by seven-ten. She takes hers from seven-ten to seven-forty.
He uses it again for two minutes at seven-forty-five. She uses it for
five more minutes at seven-fifty-five.

The schedule has evolved over eighteen months. It works now. It
didn't at first. There were three or four incidents. One time she
took thirty extra minutes because she got a work call in there. Once
he used up the last of the toilet paper and didn't replace it.

They talked. They set new rules. Neither of them wanted to be the
one who was harder about it. But they were both firm because a shared
bathroom is a real limit.

Now she buys the toilet paper. He buys the cleaning supplies. The
schedule is unspoken but stable.

They are not close friends. They are polite roommates. This is
enough.

Someday one of them will move out. The other will get a solo
bathroom and appreciate it in a way that only shared-bathroom people
can.\")

  (piece
    :id \"rr-04-a-marriage-of-thirty-years\"
    :title \"A marriage of thirty years\"
    :prose
    \"They have been married thirty years. They finish each other's
sentences half the time. The other half of the time they still argue.

He has certain things she doesn't like: he leaves cabinet doors open;
he can't hear her when she's in another room; he always thinks he's
right about directions when he isn't. She has certain things he
doesn't like: she buys things and doesn't tell him; she interrupts;
she keeps the thermostat too low.

They have found a rhythm around most of it. The cabinets she closes
without saying anything. He shouts her name louder when she's in the
kitchen. The directions she ignores and does what she thinks. The
purchases he lets be. The interrupting she is trying but rarely
succeeds. The thermostat is a fight that resurfaces every winter.

The parts they got right: they laugh a lot. They read next to each
other in bed with different books. They eat breakfast together every
day, even weekends. They know each other's parents (his parents are
dead now, hers still call every Sunday). They have never had a fight
neither remembered how to end.

If you asked either of them why they've stayed, they would give a
short answer. She would say 'he's good.' He would say 'she's the
one.' Neither would elaborate.

Thirty years of small good moments make a bigger shape than either of
them could describe. That's a marriage.\")

  (piece
    :id \"rr-05-a-breakup\"
    :title \"A breakup\"
    :prose
    \"They had been together three years. They both knew for six months
that it wasn't going to last. Neither said it.

They said it on a Sunday afternoon. She said it first. He was ready.
He had been ready for a while.

They sat on the couch and cried a little. Not a lot. There was
relief in it too. They had loved each other. They still did. That
wasn't the problem. The problem was that they wanted different lives.

He offered to move out first. She said she would. He said no, he
would. They argued about who would move out until they both laughed
because it was so predictable of them.

He moved out three weeks later. He rented a smaller apartment two
neighborhoods away. She kept the apartment. She got the couch. He
got the good dishes.

They agreed to not see each other for a while. Then friends.

The first month was hard for both of them. Then it wasn't as hard.
By six months they were texting each other about small things. By a
year they were friends in the way exes sometimes become friends.

Neither dated for a while. Then they both did. Then they both had
new relationships. Then they were people they didn't recognize.

The breakup had been the right thing. Neither of them ever second-
guessed it. But sometimes she would find a small object of his in a
box and feel a tenderness that surprised her. He would too, on his
side.

Some love ends without ending completely. That's a shape too.\")

  (piece
    :id \"rr-06-a-kitchen\"
    :title \"A kitchen\"
    :prose
    \"The kitchen is small. Galley-style. Two people can be in it if they
coordinate. Three is a crowd.

There's a wooden cutting board that has been used enough that it's
warped. There's a knife the mother has sharpened many times that is
slightly shorter than it started. There's a pot on the back burner
that came from her mother.

The kitchen has certain rules. Nothing goes on top of the fridge
because things fall off. The dish drying rack lives on the counter to
the right of the sink. The salt and pepper live on the counter to the
left of the stove.

The kitchen is a working room. It has been used every day for
fourteen years. The paint on one wall is darker where the pan is
always hung. There is a small ring on the counter where a glass
sweated one summer and it stained the surface.

When the family sold the apartment they took the pot and the cutting
board and the knife. They left the rings and the paint. Some kitchen
things travel. Others belong to the room.\")

  (piece
    :id \"rr-07-a-living-room\"
    :title \"A living room\"
    :prose
    \"The living room has a couch that is not new. It has a coffee table
that came from IKEA seven years ago and is still holding up. It has a
rug that was expensive at the time but the price has been amortized
across many afternoons.

The bookshelves have books, but also other things — a framed photo of
the parents at a wedding, three small plants, a set of hardcover
novels from grandma who has died, a candle that was lit once and now
has dust on it.

The lamp on the side table doesn't quite match the other lamp. Nobody
minds.

The TV is on the wall. Underneath it are the game consoles and the
remotes. Behind the couch there is a small stack of books that got
started and never finished.

The room gets tidied on Sundays. During the week it accumulates —
mail, jackets, socks the toddler took off. Sunday is reset day.

If you took a photo of the room every day for a year you would see
it slowly age. New coffee table books. A cushion changed. The rug
darkening slightly. This is how rooms live.\")

  (piece
    :id \"rr-08-a-morning-in-a-family\"
    :title \"A morning in a family\"
    :prose
    \"The alarm goes off at six-fifteen. The mother turns it off. She
lies still for a minute. The father is still asleep.

She gets up. She goes to the bathroom. She brushes her teeth. She
starts the coffee. She checks her phone for six minutes even though
she's promised herself she'll stop doing that.

At six-forty-five she wakes the kids. The first one groans. The second
one says 'no.' She says 'yes.' They get up. They stumble to the
bathroom. There is a brief negotiation about who goes first.

By seven both kids are eating cereal. The mother has made lunches.
The father is in the shower. The dog wants to go out. She takes the
dog out because it's quick and she can do it in her slippers.

By seven-thirty the kids are dressed and the backpacks are packed and
the father is downstairs. Everyone hugs. The father walks the older
kid to school. The mother walks the younger kid to the daycare
around the corner.

By eight-fifteen the house is empty. The mother goes back inside to
finish her coffee. Ten minutes to herself. This is the reward for
the whole morning.

Then she leaves for work. The morning is over. It happens again
tomorrow.\"))
")
